### CHAPTER XXXIII.

1\. The thirty-third subject is this, that, when *there* is a place and
any risk *or* fear exists that a corpse <span
id="fr_1263"></span>[2](#fn_1253.md) is concealed beneath the ground, *one
is* to make *it* apparent *and* visible <span
id="fr_1264"></span>[3](#fn_1254.md), because it is a great good work.

2\. For it is declared in the good religion, that, *when* they conceal a
corpse beneath the ground, Spendârma*d* <span
id="fr_1265"></span>[4](#fn_1255.md), the archangel, shudders; it is just
as severe as a serpent *or* scorpion would be to any one in private
sleep <span id="fr_1266"></span>[5](#fn_1256.md), and [is
also](errata.htm#5.md) just like that to the ground. 3. When thou makest a
corpse

<span id="page_295">p. 295</span>

beneath the ground as *it were* apparent, thou makest *the ground*
liberated from that affliction.

